Sense of VisionThe sense of vision or sight in many animals is much superior than human beings. 
The members of the cat family like the lion, cat and leopard have exceptionally 
excellent night vision that helps them to hunt even in the dark. A tiger can see six 
times better than human beings at night.
Super Senses of AnimalsUnit–II : The Living World4
Just like human beings, animals also have sense organs that help them to hear, 
smell, taste, see and feel the world around them. It has been noticed that in 
animals, sense organs are sharper than humans. Their super senses help 
them to find their food, communicate with each other and protect 
themselves from their enemies.
Let's KnowLet's KnowEnvironmental Studies-527

Birds of prey like eagle, vulture, hawk etc. can see four times as far as humans can. 
An eagle can spot a mouse on the ground from high up in the sky.
Sense of SmellAnimals like cats, mice, rats, squirrels etc. have a good sense of smell. They use 
their sensitive whiskers to search for their food.
Dogs have a very strong sense of smell. Sniffer dogs are used by the police to trace 
criminals and to find things like bombs, drugs etc. 
Sharks combine their keen sense of smell with the timing to determine the 
direction of smell. They follow the nostrils that first detect the smell and thus find 
their food.
Sense of HearingMany animals use sounds in order to communicate with one another. Animals like 
monkeys make howling sounds to warn others about any danger. Dogs bark, cats 
purr, birds chirp and frogs croak to convey joy, danger, fear, anger and the need to 
mate. Deer and other grazing animals' sense of hearing provide them warning of 
the approaching predators. Fox and other hunting animals have well developed 
sense of hearing that helps them to locate their prey.
! Bats, whales and dolphins make a loud sound. The echo of the sound helps 
them to locate their food as well as avoid the obstacles on the way.
An eagle can focus on the prey in front as well as on objects on either 
side of it without moving its head.

(Knowledge)Sense of Touch
! Cat's whiskers and the stiffer hair along its body are great at feeling around. 
They can sense a change in the air currents very fast. This helps them feel 
their way around in the dark.
Environmental Studies-528

Sense of Taste
! A catfish is the greatest 'super taster' in the world. 
Catfish have a unique taste reception system. They 
have taste receptors not only in their mouth but 
their entire body is covered in them.
! Bees have a strong sense of taste. They have taste 
sensors on their antennae and on their front feet. 
Some worker bees bring nectar for the other bees to taste. If the bees like the 
taste, then they all go to collect the nectar .
! A butterfly tastes the food with its feet as most of the taste buds are present 
on its feet.
! Cockroaches, spiders and many other insects have hair on their legs. The hair 
help them to feel out their surroundings. This sense of 
touch is also called tactile sense.
! Snakes can feel the smallest vibrations in the ground 
with the help of a bone in their jaw. It is called the 
hearing bone.
! Sharks have well developed touch receptors located in their skin, all over 
their body. They use these sensors to feel water currents and temperature 
changes.
Do Animals Sleep?
Like human beings, animals also need sleep to refresh themselves . Different 
animals have different ways of sleeping.
! Horses sleep while standing.
! Cows sleep with their eyes open.
! Bats hang themselves upside down and sleep.
! A giraffe sleeps with one of its eyes open and both ears moving.
! Migratory birds need to cover long distances, so they sleep while flying.
! Fish and snakes do not have eyelids, so they sleep with their eyes open.
! Whales and dolphins do not sleep completely. Their brains are half awake 
which enables them to keep on swimming in water and reminds them to 
come to the surface for breathing.
Environmental Studies-529

Group Behaviour in AnimalsSome animals live together and move around in groups for various reasons such 
as–
! They feel safe and protected in large groups.
! Most of the grazing animals like cows, sheep buffaloes, deer, zebras, horses 
etc. move in groups called herds for food, water and shelter.
! Living in groups helps them to take care of their young ones in a better way.
! Social animals like honeybees, termites and ants live in large groups called 
colonies. They share their work in the group. Some get food for the group, the 
others protect and look after the group.
! Some animals like lizards escape unfavourable climatic conditions such as 
severe cold by sleeping for long durations of time. This sleep-like state can 
last an entire season. This winter sleep is called hibernation. Animals like 
bears, snakes, bees and bats hibernate.
! Some animals like snails, earthworms, salamander, desert tortoise and 
crocodiles sleep through hot summer months to escape the heat. This 
summer sleep is called aestivation.
! Some animals like owls, bats and rats are inactive during the day but are very 
active at night. Such animals are called nocturnal animals.
Honeybees– Honeybees live in beehives. Every beehive has on Queen Bee that lays 
eggs. There are only a few males in the hive. Most of the bees in the hive are 
worker-bees. The worker-bees work all the day. They make the hive and also look 
after the baby bees. They collect nectar from the flowers. Once their stomachs are 
full, they spit out the nectar into the cells of their hives. After a few days, this nectar 
turns into honey. Without worker-bees there would be neither hive nor any nectar 
collection.
Ants– Ants live and work together like honey bees. The Queen Ant lays the eggs. 
The Soldier Ants look after and guard the ants nest. The Worker Ants are always 
busy looking for food and bringing it to the nest. 
Termites and wasps also live like this.
Social Behaviour of Some AnimalsEnvironmental Studies-530

Terrestrial PlantsPlants that grow in mountain regions— The 
weather in mountains is normally very cold and 
windy. Snowfall also occurs in some areas. Trees 
that grow here have to survive in cold. Pine, 
spruce, cedar and fir are some plants that grow 
in mountain regions.
Adaptation in Plants5
Different plants grow in different regions. The plants growing in a particular 
region develop some special features that help them adjust to their 
surroundings and survive.
The process of developing special features in the body to adjust in the 
surroundings is called adaptation. Let's study about the special features of 
some plants growing in different surroundings.
We can divide the plants in two categories—
 
1. Terrestrial plants — The plants that grow on land. 
 
2. Aquatic plants— The plants that grow in water.
(Knowledge)Let's KnowLet's KnowEnvironmental Studies-535Unit–II : The Living World

Special features—
! Trees are tall, thin and straight.
! They are cone shaped that helps the snow to slide off easily. Due to the 
conical shape they are called conifers.
! They bear cones instead of flowers. Cones have seeds inside them.
! They have needle shaped leaves which have a waxy coating to prevent 
damage from water.
Plants that grow in plains— Trees like banyan, neem, peepal, mango etc. grow in 
the warmer climate of the plains.
Special features—
! They have many branches that spread around.
! Their branches have many flat and thin leaves which help in evaporation of 
excess water and keeping them cool.
! They shed their leaves in winters to protect themselves from cold.
Plants that grow in deserts— Some plants grow in hot and dry places with very 
poor rainfall. They are called xerophytes. Some examples of such plants are cactus, 
date palm, babool and keekar.
Environmental Studies-536

Exceptional features of Cactus—
! The leaves of cactus are reduced to spines to prevent the loss of water by 
transpiration.
! The stem of cactus is green, thick and fleshy which stores food and water. It 
releases this water when there is no rain.
! The green stem contains chlorophyll and instead of leaves, the stem itself 
makes food for the plant.
Plants that grow in hot and humid regions— Some plants like teak, rubber, coffee, 
tea and coconut grow in hot and humid climate.
Special features—
! These trees do not shed their leaves and remain green throughout the year. 
That is why they are called evergreen trees. 
Plants that grow in marshy regions— Marshy 
places have clayey soil and plenty of water. 
Mangrove trees grow in the marshy regions.
Special features—
! The roots of these plants spread out deep under the ground in search of 
water.
! They have small reduced leaves.
Environmental Studies-537

Special features—
! In such water logged places, the soil does not allow the roots to breathe; so 
the roots grow above the soil and breathe through the tiny openings at their 
tips. Such roots are called breathing roots.
Aquatic PlantsThere are three kinds of aquatic plants— free floating, fixed floating and 
underwater plants.
Free Floating Plants— Plants like duckweed, water hyacinth and wolffia float freely 
on water.
Special features—
! They have spongy bodies with lots of empty spaces filled with air.
! Leaves have thin waxy coating to prevent damage from water.
! The stems are reduced.
! Roots are not well developed.
Fixed Floating Plants— Some 
plants like water lily and lotus have 
roots that fix the plants in the mud 
at the bottom of the pond.
Special features—
! They have flat plate-like leaves coated with wax that prevents them from 
rotting.
! The stems are very flexible. They bend with the flow of water and thus do not 
get damaged with strong water currents.
Environmental Studies-538

! The stems are hollow and light that keeps the flowers and leaves floating on 
water.
! Stomata are present on the upper surface of the leaves for them to breathe 
easily.
Underwater (submerged) Plants— 
Plants like hydrilla and tape grass 
grow completely underwater.
Special features—
! Their roots fix them in the muddy soil.
! Their leaves arise in clusters from the roots and do not have stomata.
! They breathe through the small air spaces on their body surface. 
Some Special PlantsInsectivorous Plants— Venus flytrap, Sundew and the Pitcher plant are examples 
of such plants. They have green leaves that make food for them. However, they 
grow in places where the soil is poor in nitrogen and other minerals needed by 
plants. To get these minerals, they trap insects for food. Hence, these plants are 
called insectivorous plants.
Venus flytrap has leaves that are folded into two 
halves. The leaves have long hair like structures 
on their edges. When an insect touches the hair, 
the leaf shuts, trapping the insect inside.
In

pitcher plants,
with a lid. When an insect goes inside the 
pitcher, the lid closes and the insect is trapped.
Environmental Studies-539

Sensitive plant—Touch-me-not plant is a highly 
sensitive plant that responds to touch very 
quickly. If we touch the leaves of this plant, they 
droop rapidly.

From Taste to Digestion6
Digestive SystemLet's KnowLet's KnowThe food we eat cannot be used by our body directly. It needs to be broken 
down into a simpler form. The process of breaking down of food into a simpler 
form that can be used by our body is called digestion. The organ system that 
helps in digestion of food is called digestive system.
The digestive system has many organs that work together in digesting food. Let us 
see how food is digested through digestive system. 
Environmental Studies-544Unit–II : The Living World

ExcretionThe wastes which are produced inside the body of the living organisms need to be 
removed from time to time. If these wastes are not removed, they may become 
toxic or poisonous for the body. The process of removing the wastes from the body 
is called excretion.
The main excretory organs in humans are–
! 
It excretes excess amount of water, salt 
Skin– 
and urea in the form of sweat.
! 
Carbon dioxide produced during 
Lungs– 
respiration is excreted out through the lungs 
with the help of nose.
! The digestion of the food starts in the 
mouth. When we chew the food, salive 
in the mouth mixes with the food. This 
makes food softer and easier to 
swallow. Saliva also changes the 
insoluble starch present in the food into 
soluble sugars.
! The food then passes into the stomach 
through the food pipe. The stomach is a 
hollow, muscular, bag like structure.
! In the stomach, digestive juices 
(secreted by stomach) get mixed with 
the food and further break down the 
food into smaller particles.
! From the stomach, the food passes into 
a long, coiled tube called the small 
intestine. Here, the food is mixed with more digestive juices. Some of these 
juices are produced in the small intestine and some are produced by the liver 
and pancreas. These juices help to completely digest our food.
! The digested food is absorbed by the walls of the small intestine. Thus the 
process of digestion ends here and the undigested food is passed into the 
large intestine and is thrown out from the body through the anus.

! Have your food at fixed hours.
! Eat a balanced diet.

! Drink plenty of water.
! Chew your food properly before swallowing.
! Do not overeat.
Tips for Proper Functioning of Excretory System
! Never hold back your urine.
! Exercise daily.
! Drink plenty of water that helps in removal of toxic substances from the body.
! Wash your undergarments daily.
! Clean the toilet everyday otherwise germs will spread and may cause 
diseases.
